incey's Confessions of an English Opium Eater, and Bronte's Villette, Sudan shows how the imaginative subject is based on a sense of exoticism created by a pervasive fear of what is foreign. Indeed, as Sudan clarifies, xenophobia is the underpinning not only of nationalism and imperialism but of Romantic subjectivity as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEnglish literaturex18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturex19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aExoticism in literature. 0aXenophobiazGreat BritainxHistoryx18th century. 0aXenophobiazGreat BritainxHistoryx19th century. 0aXenophobiazGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 4aCultural Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220376940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812203769423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812203769.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041354-0  Penn Press eBook-Package Literature  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  